posts.name: D_Price (1708 Co-Lead Mentor)
posts.cooked:
I think I understand your questions.

Material selection: The choice of material for a robot part will depend on various factors such as strength, weight, stiffness, and cost. For example, aluminum is a popular material for FRC robots due to its strength-to-weight ratio, while carbon fiber is a lightweight and stiff option for certain applications. It‚Äôs important to select materials that are appropriate for the specific needs of the robot and can be effectively manufactured with the available resources.

Manufacturing processes: The manufacturing process for a robot part can also impact its quality and performance. CNC machining is a popular and precise method for creating complex parts from a wide range of materials, but it can also be time-consuming and expensive. Other options such as laser cutting, waterjet cutting, and 3D printing may be more suitable for simpler parts or prototypes. Our team actually utilizes both CNC machining for large scale intricate parts while some of our smaller items are nylonx 3d printed.

In my opinion our most valuable machines in our team‚Äôs arsenal are:

CNC Machine - Is able to machine our precise parts that fit motors and bearings.

Horizontal Lathe

3D Printers (We have 5 of them.)

Drill Press

Laser Engraver (Wood and other fun projects)

posts.name: Ardiano Works
posts.cooked:
I would actually buy off the shelf components as much as I can, get the bot mechanically and electrically done so we can practice, practice and practice.

Lathe is pretty specific machine. Unless you are doing custom shafts, CNC router/mill is more versatile. I would actually buy a good manual mill instead of CNC anything. in other word, I would buy a good old Bridgeport knee mill for the same price of modern CNC routers. Manual mill is easier for doing rework operation and creating one off design which is what you need to quickly iterate your design, plus it really gives student a true hands on experience .

Plan out time to get it in set it up tune it in learn how to use it etc. Get all that straightened out first and you‚Äôll be on your way to incorporating cnc magic into your bots.

posts.name: Zach Hoegberg
posts.cooked:
Slight terminology note here:

D_Price:

CNC machining is a popular and precise method for creating complex parts from a wide range of materials, but it can also be time-consuming and expensive. Other options such as laser cutting, waterjet cutting, and 3D printing

All of the options you mention here fall under the umbrella of CNC machines. CNC stands for Computer Numeric Control and simply means that the machine is controlled by a computer rather than manually turning handles. Mills, lathes, sheet metal brakes, even drill presses can be CNC or manual machines. When you say that your ‚ÄúCNC machine‚Äù is the most valuable tool in your team‚Äôs arsenal, I assume based on context you actually mean a CNC router, or maybe a CNC mill.
